<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Arcus Electrics Ltd (BRS 16)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:18pt 0pt 4.5pt 36pt; text-align:center; text-indent:-36pt"><a name="_Toc369879841"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from Arcus Electrics Ltd </span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">I have watched online a couple of times the House of Commons Communities and Local Government hearing on building regulations applying to electrical installations and repairs in dwellings, that was held </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">on 2"d September, and am writing to comment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">I have been registered as an electrician running my own business since the beginning of this year after retraining in 2012. Previously I had spent over twenty years working in senior roles for an international c</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">orporation in change management and strategy as well as direct product development program management and leadership.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">I started to write a letter to the four registration scheme representatives but in the end decided to write to you about what I saw. The f</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">our were trying to defend an indefensible position in my view. All the talk was about brand, choice, and competition rather than about standards and safety. Two registers of competent people with deceptively similar names does not help anybody. They do not</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> seem to be able to work together.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Whilst this brand proliferation has been going on</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Part P has been reduced in scope (does not apply to outdoors or kitchens any more).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The legal framework for electrical safety is not concrete enough (I do a lot of work fo</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">r a letting agent and landlords have no obligation for electrical testing or upgrading).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Marketing and communication is more focused on who is a competent person "who you can trust" and less on electrical safety, standards of installation, or a encouraging</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> a regime of regular testing.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">It appears that registration schemes are looking at the situation only from their own perspective, and I suggest that what is needed in the electrical industry is some bigger picture thinking and a thorough review of:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Standard</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s and clear documentation (Electrical Safety Council and IET have some good information but you have to search it out)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Registration scheme (s) (why NAPIT is somehow isolated from NICEIC and Elecsa)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Register of contractors (one only)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Clarity of regulations </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">â€” Part P, and how in practice homeowners, landlord, business owners demonstrate compliance with laws on electrical safety</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Communication (standards eg. Importance of RCDs and earthing, as well as one register of competent persons)</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><img src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAEAAAApCAYAAAD06kPSAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAAARSURBVBhXY2BgYPgPxMOCAAAekCjYGGp2OwAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==" width="1" height="40" alt="" style="margin-left:537.3pt; margin-top:385pt; position:absolute; z-index:0" /><img src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAEAAACACAYAAADK+QP0AAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjw